{"title_page": "Alfred Averill", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific-prefix = {{pre-nominal styles|MRevd|size=100%}}\n| name = Alfred Averill\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|CMG|size=100%}}\n| title = [[Archbishop of New Zealand]]\n| image = Archbishop Alfred Walter Averill passport photo (1929).jpg\n| caption = Averill in 1929\n| province = \n| diocese = \n| enthroned = \n| predecessor = [[Churchill Julius]]\n| ordination = \n| consecration = \n| consecrated_by   = \n| other_post = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name = Alfred Walter Averill\n| birth_date = 7 October 1865\n| birth_place = [[Staffordshire]], England\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1957|7|6|1865|10|7|df=y}}\n| death_place      = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n| buried           = <!-- or | tomb = -->\n| religion = [[Anglicanism]]\n| residence = \n| parents =Henry Alcock Averill &amp; Sarah Ellen Wootton\n| spouse = Mary Weir\n| children = [[Walter Averill]] (priest)<br />[[Leslie Averill]] (physician)\n| profession =  \n| alma_mater =[[St John's College, Oxford]]<br />[[Ely Theological College]]\n}}\n'''Alfred Walter Averill''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|CMG|size=85%}} (7 October 1865{{snd}}6 July 1957) was the second [[Anglican]] [[Archbishop of New Zealand]], from 1925 to 1940. He was also the fifth Anglican [[Anglican Diocese of Auckland|Bishop of Auckland]] whose [[episcopate]] spanned a 25-year period during the first half of the 20th century.<ref>{{cite news | url=| title=Most Rev. A. W. Averill Late Primate Of New Zealand | date=8 July 1957 | work= [[The Times]] | accessdate= | issue=53887| page=10 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in Castle Church, [[Staffordshire]] he was educated at [[King Edward VI High School, Stafford|King Edward VI School, Stafford]] and [[St John's College, Oxford]], where his course of study was Honour Theology.<ref name=\"50NZ\">{{cite book |last1= Archbishop Averill |first1= |authorlink1= |title= Fifty Years In New Zealand|url= |format= |accessdate=  |year=1945 |publisher=Whitcombe & Tombs |location= |language= |isbn= |oclc=  |doi= |id= |page= |pages= |chapter= |quote= |ref= |bibcode= }}</ref><ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\">{{DNZB|Limbrick|Warren E.|3a24|Alfred Walter Averill|23 April 2017||}}</ref> He [[Eights Week|rowed for his College]] and got his [[Sporting colours|colours]] for playing both [[rugby football|rugby]] and [[association football]] (soccer). He graduated in 1887, then he attended the [[Ely Theological College]].<ref name=\"50NZ\" /> He was made deacon in [[St Paul's Cathedral]] by [[Frederick Temple]], [[Bishop of London]], on the Fourth Sunday in [[Advent]] 1888;<ref name=\"50NZ\"/> and [[ordained]] [[priest]] on 22 December 1889 in London;<ref name=\"blain\">Blain, Michael. ''Blain Biographical Directory of Anglican clergy in the South Pacific \u2014 ordained before 1932'' (2019) pp. 52\u20133 (Accessed at [http://anglicanhistory.org/nz/blain_directory/directory.pdf Project Canterbury], 25 June 2019)</ref> before embarking on an [[ecclesiastical]] career with a [[curacy]] at [[St George's, Hanover Square]].<ref>{{cite news | url=| title=Newly appointed Deacons in London| date=25 December 1888 | work= [[The Times]] | accessdate= | issue=32578| page=10 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1891 he accepted a position as an assistant curate from the vicar of Holy Trinity parish, [[Dalston]] in the north-east of London. He married Mary Weir on 30 November 1893 at Christ Church [[Lancaster Gate]], London.<ref name=\"50NZ\"/>\n\nEmigrating to New Zealand in 1894, he became [[Vicar]] of [[Church of St Michael and All Angels, Christchurch|St Michael and All Angels]] in [[Christchurch]] on 2 March 1894, remaining in that post until his consecration as bishop. Additionally, he was a [[Canon (priest)|Canon]] of [[ChristChurch Cathedral]] (13 November 1902{{snd}}1909), [[Archdeacon of Akaroa]] (13 November 1902{{snd}}1909) and [[Archdeacon of Christchurch]] (7 April 1909 'til consecration).<ref name=\"blain\" />\n\nElected [[Bishop of Waiapu]] in 1909, Averill was consecrated a bishop on 16 January 1910, by [[Samuel Nevill]], [[Bishop of Dunedin]] and [[Primate of New&nbsp;Zealand]], and other bishops, at [[Waiapu Cathedral of Saint John the Evangelist, Napier|Napier Cathedral]]. Elected on 30 September 1913, he was [[Translation (ecclesiastical)|translated]] to [[Anglican Diocese of Auckland|Auckland]] on 31 January 1914, and he was further promoted to be [[Archbishop of New Zealand]]<ref name=\"blain\" /><ref name=\"50NZ\"/><ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\" /> effective 21 April 1925.<ref>https://teara.govt.nz/en/1966/averill-most-reverend-alfred-walter-cmg</ref>\n\nAt the 1925 [[Synod]], he supported amendment of the constitution of the Anglican Church of New Zealand so that it would enjoy full autonomy from the [[Church of England]].<ref name=\"50NZ\"/> He supported the creation of the [[Te P\u012bhopa o Aotearoa|bishopric of Aotearoa]] in 1928, which resulted in the appointment of [[Frederick Bennett (bishop)|Frederick Bennett]] as the [[Bishop of Aotearoa]] and the [[Spiritual Leader]] of the [[M\u0101ori people]].<ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\"/>\n\nHe engaged in dialogue with Bishop [[James Liston]] of the Roman Catholic Church and the ministers of the [[Presbyterian polity|Presbyterian]] and [[Congregationalist polity|non-episcopal Churches]]. Early in his episcopate in Auckland, he was appointed the first chairman of the Council of Christian Congregations.<ref name=\"50NZ\"/>\n\nHe served as second Archbishop and [[Primate of New&nbsp;Zealand]] until 1939, resigned his See (Auckland) effective 31 March 1940 and retired to [[Christchurch]].<ref name=\"50NZ\"/><ref name=\"blain\" />\n\n==Support of education==\n[[File:Archbishop_Alfred_Averill_and_Mary_Averill_passprt_application_(1929).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|155x155px|Archbishop Alfred Averill and Mary Averill passprt application (1929)]]\nBefore being appointed as the Bishop of Waiapu, he was a member of the governing body [[Christ's College, Christchurch]]. After his appointment as Bishop on Auckland in 1914, he became a member of the board of [[King's College, Auckland]] during the time the School moved from Remuera to its present location in [[Otahuhu]].<ref name=\"50NZ\"/>  Averill House, which was founded in 1961, was named in his honour.\n\n==Associations with organisations==\nHe supported the [[St John Ambulance]] Association and Brigade, the [[New Zealand Red Cross]], serving as a vice-president of the Auckland Branch. He was the first honorary member of the [[Rotary International|Rotary Club]] of Auckland. He also supported the Bible in State Schools League of New Zealand, the New Zealand Society for the Protection of Women and Children, the [[Royal Society of St George]] and the [[Royal Commonwealth Society|Royal Empire Society]].<ref name=\"50NZ\"/><ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\"/>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n[[File:Mary_Averill_passport_photo_(1929).jpg|thumb|Mary Averill in 1929]]\nHe was made an honorary doctor of divinity of Oxford University (1912), a sub-prelate of the [[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|Order of St John]] (1924), and an episcopal canon of [[St. George's Cathedral, Jerusalem|St George's Collegiate Church, Jerusalem]].<ref name=\"50NZ\"/><ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\"/>\n\nIn 1935, he was awarded the [[King George V Silver Jubilee Medal]].<ref name=\"EP\">{{cite news | url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=EP19350506.2.12  | title=Official jubilee medals | date=6 May 1935 | work= Evening Post | accessdate=2 July 2013 | page=4 }}</ref> Shortly before his death in 1957, he was appointed a [[Order of St Michael and St George|Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]] in the [[1957 Birthday Honours (New Zealand)|1957 Queen's Birthday Honours]].<ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\"/><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=41091 |date=13 June 1957 |page=3413 |supp=3}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nAlfred was married to Mary (nee Weir). Alfred's eldest son, [[Walter Averill]], became a priest and served as [[Archdeacon of Timaru]]; a second son, [[Leslie Averill]], served with the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]] towards the end of the First World War, and played a key role in the [[Capture of Le Quesnoy (1918)|capture of Le Quesnoy]] in France. He later became a prominent medical administrator and community leader in Christchurch.<ref name=\"DNZB LAverill\">{{DNZB|Rice|Geoffrey W.|5a25|Leslie Cecil Lloyd Averill|23 April 2013||Geoffrey Rice}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Diocese of Waiapu|Bishop of Waiapu]]|before=[[William Leonard Williams]]|after=[[William Walmsley Sedgwick]]|years=1910&ndash;1914}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Anglican Diocese of Auckland|Bishop of Auckland, NZ]]|before=[[Owen Thomas Lloyd Crossley]]|after=[[William John Simkin]]|years=1914&ndash;1940}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Archbishop of New Zealand]]|before=[[Churchill Julius]]|after=[[Campbell West-Watson]]|years=1925&ndash;1940}}\n{{end}}\n{{Archdeacons of Akaroa}}\n{{Archdeacons of Christchurch}}\n{{Bishops of Waiapu}}\n{{Anglican Bishops of Auckland, NZ}}\n{{Primates and Archbishops of New Zealand}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Averill, Alfred Walter}}\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:People from the Borough of Stafford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:19th-century English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Akaroa]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Waiapu]]\n[[Category:Anglican bishops of Auckland]]\n[[Category:Primates of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from Auckland]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific-prefix = {{pre-nominal styles|MRevd|size=100%}}\n| name = Alfred Averill\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|CMG|size=100%}}\n| title = [[Archbishop of New Zealand]]\n| image =\n| caption = \n| province = \n| diocese = \n| enthroned = \n| predecessor = [[Churchill Julius]]\n| ordination = \n| consecration = \n| consecrated_by   = \n| other_post = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name = Alfred Walter Averill\n| birth_date = 7 October 1865\n| birth_place = [[Staffordshire]], England\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1957|7|6|1865|10|7|df=y}}\n| death_place      = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n| buried           = <!-- or | tomb = -->\n| religion = [[Anglicanism]]\n| residence = \n| parents =Henry Alcock Averill &amp; Sarah Ellen Wootton\n| spouse = Mary Weir\n| children = [[Walter Averill]] (priest)<br />[[Leslie Averill]] (physician)\n| profession =  \n| alma_mater =[[St John's College, Oxford]]<br />[[Ely Theological College]]\n}}\n'''Alfred Walter Averill''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|CMG|size=85%}} (7 October 1865{{snd}}6 July 1957) was the second [[Anglican]] [[Archbishop of New Zealand]], from 1925 to 1940. He was also the fifth Anglican [[Anglican Diocese of Auckland|Bishop of Auckland]] whose [[episcopate]] spanned a 25-year period during the first half of the 20th century.<ref>{{cite news | url=| title=Most Rev. A. W. Averill Late Primate Of New Zealand | date=8 July 1957 | work= [[The Times]] | accessdate= | issue=53887| page=10 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in Castle Church, [[Staffordshire]] he was educated at [[King Edward VI High School, Stafford|King Edward VI School, Stafford]] and [[St John's College, Oxford]], where his course of study was Honour Theology.<ref name=\"50NZ\">{{cite book |last1= Archbishop Averill |first1= |authorlink1= |title= Fifty Years In New Zealand|url= |format= |accessdate=  |year=1945 |publisher=Whitcombe & Tombs |location= |language= |isbn= |oclc=  |doi= |id= |page= |pages= |chapter= |quote= |ref= |bibcode= }}</ref><ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\">{{DNZB|Limbrick|Warren E.|3a24|Alfred Walter Averill|23 April 2017||}}</ref> He [[Eights Week|rowed for his College]] and got his [[Sporting colours|colours]] for playing both [[rugby football|rugby]] and [[association football]] (soccer). He graduated in 1887, then he attended the [[Ely Theological College]].<ref name=\"50NZ\" /> He was made deacon in [[St Paul's Cathedral]] by [[Frederick Temple]], [[Bishop of London]], on the Fourth Sunday in [[Advent]] 1888;<ref name=\"50NZ\"/> and [[ordained]] [[priest]] on 22 December 1889 in London;<ref name=\"blain\">Blain, Michael. ''Blain Biographical Directory of Anglican clergy in the South Pacific \u2014 ordained before 1932'' (2019) pp. 52\u20133 (Accessed at [http://anglicanhistory.org/nz/blain_directory/directory.pdf Project Canterbury], 25 June 2019)</ref> before embarking on an [[ecclesiastical]] career with a [[curacy]] at [[St George's, Hanover Square]].<ref>{{cite news | url=| title=Newly appointed Deacons in London| date=25 December 1888 | work= [[The Times]] | accessdate= | issue=32578| page=10 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1891 he accepted a position as an assistant curate from the vicar of Holy Trinity parish, [[Dalston]] in the north-east of London. He married Mary Weir on 30 November 1893 at Christ Church [[Lancaster Gate]], London.<ref name=\"50NZ\"/>\n\nEmigrating to New Zealand in 1894, he became [[Vicar]] of [[Church of St Michael and All Angels, Christchurch|St Michael and All Angels]] in [[Christchurch]] on 2 March 1894, remaining in that post until his consecration as bishop. Additionally, he was a [[Canon (priest)|Canon]] of [[ChristChurch Cathedral]] (13 November 1902{{snd}}1909), [[Archdeacon of Akaroa]] (13 November 1902{{snd}}1909) and [[Archdeacon of Christchurch]] (7 April 1909 'til consecration).<ref name=\"blain\" />\n\nElected [[Bishop of Waiapu]] in 1909, Averill was consecrated a bishop on 16 January 1910, by [[Samuel Nevill]], [[Bishop of Dunedin]] and [[Primate of New&nbsp;Zealand]], and other bishops, at [[Waiapu Cathedral of Saint John the Evangelist, Napier|Napier Cathedral]]. Elected on 30 September 1913, he was [[Translation (ecclesiastical)|translated]] to [[Anglican Diocese of Auckland|Auckland]] on 31 January 1914, and he was further promoted to be [[Archbishop of New Zealand]]<ref name=\"blain\" /><ref name=\"50NZ\"/><ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\" /> effective 21 April 1925.<ref>https://teara.govt.nz/en/1966/averill-most-reverend-alfred-walter-cmg</ref>\n\nAt the 1925 [[Synod]], he supported amendment of the constitution of the Anglican Church of New Zealand so that it would enjoy full autonomy from the [[Church of England]].<ref name=\"50NZ\"/> He supported the creation of the [[Te P\u012bhopa o Aotearoa|bishopric of Aotearoa]] in 1928, which resulted in the appointment of [[Frederick Bennett (bishop)|Frederick Bennett]] as the [[Bishop of Aotearoa]] and the [[Spiritual Leader]] of the [[M\u0101ori people]].<ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\"/>\n\nHe engaged in dialogue with Bishop [[James Liston]] of the Roman Catholic Church and the ministers of the [[Presbyterian polity|Presbyterian]] and [[Congregationalist polity|non-episcopal Churches]]. Early in his episcopate in Auckland, he was appointed the first chairman of the Council of Christian Congregations.<ref name=\"50NZ\"/>\n\nHe served as second Archbishop and [[Primate of New&nbsp;Zealand]] until 1939, resigned his See (Auckland) effective 31 March 1940 and retired to [[Christchurch]].<ref name=\"50NZ\"/><ref name=\"blain\" />\n\n==Support of education==\nBefore being appointed as the Bishop of Waiapu, he was a member of the governing body [[Christ's College, Christchurch]]. After his appointment as Bishop on Auckland in 1914, he became a member of the board of [[King's College, Auckland]] during the time the School moved from Remuera to its present location in [[Otahuhu]].<ref name=\"50NZ\"/>  Averill House, which was founded in 1961, was named in his honour.\n\n==Associations with organisations==\nHe supported the [[St John Ambulance]] Association and Brigade, the [[New Zealand Red Cross]], serving as a vice-president of the Auckland Branch. He was the first honorary member of the [[Rotary International|Rotary Club]] of Auckland. He also supported the Bible in State Schools League of New Zealand, the New Zealand Society for the Protection of Women and Children, the [[Royal Society of St George]] and the [[Royal Commonwealth Society|Royal Empire Society]].<ref name=\"50NZ\"/><ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\"/>\n\n==Honours and awards==\nHe was made an honorary doctor of divinity of Oxford University (1912), a sub-prelate of the [[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|Order of St John]] (1924), and an episcopal canon of [[St. George's Cathedral, Jerusalem|St George's Collegiate Church, Jerusalem]].<ref name=\"50NZ\"/><ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\"/>\n\nIn 1935, he was awarded the [[King George V Silver Jubilee Medal]].<ref name=\"EP\">{{cite news | url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=EP19350506.2.12  | title=Official jubilee medals | date=6 May 1935 | work= Evening Post | accessdate=2 July 2013 | page=4 }}</ref> Shortly before his death in 1957, he was appointed a [[Order of St Michael and St George|Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]] in the [[1957 Birthday Honours (New Zealand)|1957 Queen's Birthday Honours]].<ref name=\"DNZB AAverill\"/><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=41091 |date=13 June 1957 |page=3413 |supp=3}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nAlfred's eldest son, [[Walter Averill]], became a priest and served as [[Archdeacon of Timaru]]; a second son, [[Leslie Averill]], served with the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]] towards the end of the First World War, and played a key role in the [[Capture of Le Quesnoy (1918)|capture of Le Quesnoy]] in France. He later became a prominent medical administrator and community leader in Christchurch.<ref name=\"DNZB LAverill\">{{DNZB|Rice|Geoffrey W.|5a25|Leslie Cecil Lloyd Averill|23 April 2013||Geoffrey Rice}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n